('Samus, N.; Kravtsov, V.; Ipatov, A.; Smirnov, O.; Alcaino, G.; Liller, W.; Alvarado, F.', 'A CCD BVI color-magnitude study of the metal-rich globular cluster NGC 5927', 'Astronomy and Astrophysics Supplement, v.119, 1996, p.191-197', '"http://cdsads.u-strasbg.fr/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1996A%26AS..119..191S"', 108, '2007-10-04 10:15:46', 1996, 'ngc5927', '0000-00-00', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 128),
('Alcaino, Gonzalo; Liller, William; Alvarado, Franklin; Wenderoth, Erich', 'BV CCD photometry of the low-latitude globular cluster NGC 5946', 'Astronomical Journal, vol. 102, Oct. 1991, p. 1371-1380, 1576, 1577', '"http://cdsads.u-strasbg.fr/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1991AJ....102.1371A"', 109, '2007-10-04 10:15:46', 1991, 'ngc5946', '2013-11-04', NULL, NULL, '', 'BV CCD photometry of the previously unstudied highly concentrated low-galactic-latitude globular cluster NGC 5946 observed with the 2.2-m Max Planck Institut telescope is presented. The photometry extends to V of about 21.5, reaching about 4 mag below the brighter edge of the horizontal branch. The latter extends continuously from blue to red color indices in the magnitude range between 17.0 and 18.5. The adopted reddening of E(B-V) = 0.53 + or - 0.05 places the cluster at 10.7 kpc from the sun and 5.8 kpc from the galactic center, assuming R0 = 8.5 kpc. It is suggested that the cluster is more metal-poor than previously believed. When the giant branch of NGC 5946 is matched with that of other globular clusters, much better agreement is found with clusters of low metallicity than with those of intermediate metallicity.', 229),
('Ortolani, S.; Bica, E.; Barbuy, B.', 'BH 176 and AM-2: globular or open clusters?', 'Astronomy and Astrophysics, 1995, v.300, p.726', '"http://cdsads.u-strasbg.fr/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1995A%26A...300..726O"', 110, '2007-10-04 10:15:46', 1995, 'BH176', '2013-12-06', NULL, NULL, '', 'We have obtained VI photometry for two low Galactic latitude star clusters: BH 176 and AM-2, using the 2.2m and the 3.5m NTT telescopes at ESO. Their VI colour-magnitude diagrams reveal that: BH 176 may be a globular cluster, or a borderline object between a globular cluster and a disk cluster, showing a red horizontal branch and an extended red giant branch. We estimate E(B-V)=0.77 and dsun_=13.4kpc. AM-2 appears to be an intermediate age open cluster, for which a reddening E(B-V)=0.44 and dsun_=12.4kpc are estimated. It is located in the outer regions of the Galactic disk.', 230),
